  "prompt": "Why do Malaysians and Singaporeans refer to Indonesians as \"Indon\"?",
  "response": "The term \"Indon\" is a colloquial abbreviation used by some Malaysians and Singaporeans to refer to Indonesians. The origins of this term are not entirely clear, but it is thought to be a shorthand derived from \"Indonesia.\" \n\nHowever, it's important to note that this term can be considered derogatory and offensive by many Indonesians. They prefer to be called \"Indonesian\" rather than \"Indon,\" as the latter can carry negative connotations and historical baggage. Indonesians have expressed their discomfort with the term, and respectful communication generally involves using their full nationality.\n\nCultural sensitivity and respect are crucial when referring to individuals and groups from different countries and ethnic backgrounds. It's always best to use terms that are preferred by the people themselves to ensure positive and respectful interaction.",
